 modernity and development, their breakdowns and absences reveal the underbelly of progress, liberal equality, and economic growth. This tension, between aspiration and failure, makes infrastructure a productive location for social theory. Contributing to the everyday lives of infrastructure across four continents, some of the leading anthropologists of infrastructure demonstrate in The Promise of Infrastructure how these more-than-human assemblages made over more-than-human lifetimes offer new opportunities to theorize time, politics, and promise in the contemporary moment.A School for Advanced Research Advanced SeminarContributors. Nikhil Anand, Hannah Appel, Geoffrey C. Bowker, Dominic Boyer, Akhil Gupta, Penny Harvey, Brian Larkin, Christina Schwenkel, Antina von Schnitzler  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aEconomic developmentxSocial aspects. 0aEthnology. 0aInfrastructure (Economics)xPolitical aspects. 0aInfrastructure (Economics)xSocial aspects. 0aTechnological complexityxSocial aspects. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAnand, Nikhil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAppel, Hannah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGupta, Akhil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478002031zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478002031423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478002031.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles